node.text:
A new piece by The Guardian explores how many Native American tribes across the country are using their authority as sovereign nations to enforce COVID-19 mandates within their borders. Since the pandemic began, Indigenous groups have been some of the hardest-hit communities in the U.S. when it comes to COVID-19. According to a February 2021 report, 1 in every 475 Native Americans was dying of COVID-19, the fastest rate of any demographic in the country.⁠
However, while many states have seen policies like mask mandates become local battleground issues, many tribal nations have been able to aggressively implement them — even when geographically located in states that otherwise are banning such mandates. That's because the U.S. constitution grants federally-recognized the same self-governing power as states. ⁠
A prime example is the Navajo Nation, which shares much of its border with Arizona, a state which has no mask mandate in schools. According to The Guardian's report, the Navajo Nation has implemented a mask mandate in 133 schools across 27,000 sq miles and found zero instances of a COVID spread incident in any of them so far this school year.⁠
⁠
'With any war, any battles, you got to be equipped, you got to have your armor, and you got to have your weapons,' Navajo Nation President Jonathan Nez told The Guardian. 'And one of the armors that we have is the vaccine. And one of the weapons that we have is the mask and the hand sanitizers. And so we framed it in that way to where our elders can understand what we’re dealing with. And they assisted and helped us talk to our younger generation.'⁠
⁠
⁠
#nativeamerican #navajo #indigenous #covid19

node.text:
A new report finds that air pollution is killing people at a faster rate than smoking, car crashes, or HIV/AIDS. Prof. Michael Greenstone at the University of Chicago and his colleagues developed the Air Quality Life Index (AQLI), which looks at the death rates in certain areas compared to their respective levels of air pollution. The research shows that people living in polluted areas have a higher propensity for heart and lung problems, which has been cutting short the lives of billions of people by up to 6 years. ⁠
⁠
'Coal is the source of the problem in most parts of the world,' said Greenstone, via The Guardian. 'If these [health] costs were embedded in prices, coal would be uncompetitive in almost all parts of the world.'⁠
The report says residents in India are the most adversely affected by air pollution, with the average citizen losing an estimated 6 years off their lives due to it. In China, air pollution can cut off an estimated 2.6 years from an average resident's longevity.⁠
⁠
⁠
#airpollution #airquality #pollution #smoke #smog
